snippet.textDisplay:
In So What, Ha Seul's absence is apparent and a little heartbreaking. On the other hand, below are my observations connecting So What with Ha Seul's Let Me In--how she is still present in this comeback even with her hiatus as she focuses on taking care of her mental health.

So What and Mirror Imagery
In the MV for Let Me In, Ha Seul was wearing a Red dress because she's Kim Lip's mirror. So What hinted on this mirror imagery by dressing Choerry (Purple) and Hyun Jin (Yellow) in the same outfits and mirroring each other's moves, and dressing up Yeo Jin (Orange) like Jin Soul (Blue) in Singing in the Rain and dyeing her hair blonde. In a color wheel with all the primary and secondary colors, Purple and Yellow are across from each other, so are Blue and Orange, and Red and Green.

Both Kim Lip and Ha Seul were transported by Hyun Jin (the Yellow Jeep in Girl Front and Let Me In) to the middle of nowhere to search for other colors--the other Loonas, the missing memories of Hee Jin's creation. Kim Lip to a HOT, BURNING, arid desert and Ha Seul to an ICY, COLD, frozen tundra. Both have extreme temperatures, and yet extreme opposites, that would be hard to survive in.

Ha Seul shot Kim Lip in one side of the Mobius. She shot a blonde girl with feathers, indicating that she shot a bird, in this instance, an owl (Kim Lip). The birds of the Loonaverse are shooting each other. Ha Seul could seem doubtful or jealous of the cool confident mirror of herself, that she shot down that possibility, before she could even transform into that. Kim Lip shot Ha Seul, the doubting, insecure mirror of herself that possibly stops her from carrying out her mission of summoning a new phase of the moon.

In Sweet Crazy Love, Kim Lip sings, "All I see are your lips through all your wordplay." Ha Seul was actually playing with words in the lyrics of Let Me In, "The Girl is the Boy's Girl" turns into "The Girl is the Boy's wish." I don't think Ha Seul was referring to gender, rather, she was referring to characteristics that tradition has assigned to men and women, like the Yin and Yang. She was wishing to be more confident and take-charge (which for years, was a "man-like" characteristic) like Kim Lip.

BONUS CONTENT: In LoonaTV, Kim Lip reminded Ha Seul during their Butterfly era makeovers to stop acting childish because her short hair makes her look chic and elegant. It was like the reflection talking to the self to take charge of the change in looks and in heart.

Connecting LET ME IN and SO WHAT
Iceland is a place of fire and ice. It's position in the northern hemisphere makes it prone to harsh winters, and yet, the tectonic plates below gave rise to plenty of volcanoes. In Let Me In, it was frozen because when Ha Seul sings, according to Loona lore, she brings rain. The snow that we see in other music videos are actually caused by her singing. Rain turns to snow when it's cold. In So What, Olivia burned Iceland to bring warmth and light to Ha Seul's cold, freezing heart (as seen in the lyrics of Let Me In). That's why the feather in the end of So What caught fire (was warmed) but instead of being consumed, it was renewed, like a Phoenix rising from the ashes. Remember that Ha Seul is a plain white bird, with no specific species. This means that she encompasses all the birds in the Loonaverse (The Owl, The Swan, and The Penguin) and she can be any type of bird. This also makes me hopeful that she will come back stronger than before for their future works.

I think "Burn Yourself" from So What means taking the painful path to healing and forgiveness for the sins and temptations of the Loona girls. Once a fire is started, the warmth and light spreads to the cold and darkness, making a person FREE. When a person is free, they can share more of themselves. I think that's why the burning moon in So What spread like meteors all over the world. So that's there'd be more Loonas--as BlockBerry puts it--those who listen to their music, and those that are inspired, enlightened, and encouraged by their message.

1) Heejin is living that ViVid city-girl life that's more street-wear edge than parisan [fantasy].
2) Yves rises to embody the black swan that leads the ballet dancers in white [REBEL AGAINST EDEN].
3) Kim Lip goes from dancing in broken ruins to the kind of expensive mansion she killed a rich man for
4) Jin Soul finally has friends in her train.

snippet.textDisplay:
i think the loonaverse and especially the 'loop' is a metaphor for the social norms placed on girls. through the different era it shows the evolution of a girl living in the 'loop'. this loop can evolve over time and become looser, but it is very difficult to break. in the loonaverse, the moon holds the loop together.

during 1/3 she doesn't know about the loop or just accepts it. she acts cute and lovely, like a 'good girl' is supposed to.

during odd eye circle she becomes aware of it and acts more 'girl crush' as a way of defiance, but eventually that just becomes part of the loop.

during yyxy she learns to love herself instead of somebody else. she wants to fly out of the loop.

during hi high she wants somebody else to lead her high, out of the loop. this doesn't work.

during butterfly she realises she has to fly out of the loop herself and encourages others to do so too.

during so what she realises that flying out of the loop isn't enough. she realises she has to break the loop for good. the only way to do so is to sacrifice herself. she can't accept the fate of the moon, and she has to burn herself to escape her fate.
